
@{
    ViewBag.Title = "Index1";
    Layout = "~/Views/Shared/_Layout.cshtml";
}
<link href="~/Content/blog.css" rel="stylesheet" />

<style>


    .blog-post {
        margin-bottom: 1rem;
    }

    .table-sm th {
        padding: 30px 40px;
    }

    .custom-control {
        display: inline-block;
        padding-left: 35px;
    }

    .btn-primary, .btn-primary:hover, .btn-primary:not(:disabled):not(.disabled):active {
        color: #fff;
        background-color: #ffcd3c;
        border-color: #ffcd3c;
    }

    .chen-nav-link:hover {
        color: #405d7e !important;
    }
</style>

<div class="container" style="margin-top:40px;margin-bottom:40px;">
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-md-12 blog-main">
            <h2 class="blog-post-title">
                Blood Alcohol Content
            </h2>
            <span style="margin-bottom: 2rem; display: block; width: 20%; height: 5px; background-color: #edab00;"></span>
            <div class="blog-post" style="word-wrap: break-word; word-break: normal;">
                <p class="lead">
                    Blood alcohol concentration(BAC) is the level of alcohol in your bloodstream and a good
                    indicator of intoxication. BAC is what police use in roadside breath tests to measure drunken
                    driving. If a person has a Blood alcohol concentration of 0.05% (point 0 five), then there is
                    0.05 g of alcohol in every 100 ml of blood(Australia’s upper legal limit for driving) .
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-12 blog-main">
            <h3 class="h3" style="margin-bottom:1rem;">
                Blood Alcohol Concentration Likely Behaviour Table
            </h3>
            <div class="table-responsive">
                <table class="table table-striped table-sm">
                    <thead style="background-color: #edab00;">
                        <tr>
                            <th>BAC*</th>
                            <th>Likely effects of Intoxication</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tr>
                        <td>0.02–0.05 g / 100 ml</td>
                        <td>
                            <ul>
                                <li> Cheerful, relaxed, pleasant feelings of happiness and wellbeing</li>
                                <li> Decreasing inhibitions.</li>
                                <li> Judgment increasingly impaired.</li>
                                <li> Increased chance of accidents.</li>
                                <li> Impaired coordination.</li>
                                <li>
                                    BAC* 0.05 g / 100 ml = legal limit for driving (if fully licensed) in all
                                    Australian states and territories.
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>0.1–0.2 g / 100 ml</td>
                        <td>
                            <ul>
                                <li> Ataxia</li>
                                <li> Decreased ability to appropriately interpret and react to surroundings.</li>
                                <li> Poor judgment.</li>
                                <li> Loss of ‘self-control’.</li>
                                <li> Slurred speech.</li>
                                <li>
                                    Increasingly unpredictable behaviour.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    Labile mood.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    Potential for aggression.
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>0.2–0.3 g / 100 ml</td>
                        <td>
                            <ul>
                                <li> Marked ataxia and slurred speech.</li>
                                <li> Poor judgment.</li>
                                <li> Labile mood.</li>
                                <li> Nausea and Vomiting.</li>
                                <li> Double vision.</li>
                                <li>
                                    Memory loss
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>0.3–0.4 g / 100 ml</td>
                        <td>
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    Stage 1 anaesthesia (sleepiness, poor response to external stimuli,
                                    oblivion).
                                </li>
                                <li> Memory lapse.</li>
                                <li> Labile mood.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>> 0.40 g / 100 ml</td>
                        <td>
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    Respiratory failure.
                                </li>
                                <li> Coma.</li>
                                <li> Possible death.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </td>
                    </tr>
                </table>
            </div>

        </div>
        <div class="col-md-12 blog-main">
            <h3 class="h3" style="margin-bottom:1rem;">
                How to stay below 0.05?
            </h3>
            <div class="blog-post" style="word-wrap: break-word; word-break: normal;">
                <p>
                    ➢ For men of average size: Limit your consumption to 2 standard drinks in the first
                    hour, then 1 standard drink thereafter.
                </p>
                <p>➢ For women of average size: No more than one standard drink per hour.</p>
                <p style="font-weight:bold;">Note: This is only a guide. You might still register above 0.05% even if you follow this.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="col-md-12 blog-main">
            <h3 class="h3" style="margin-bottom:1rem;">
                What factors affect Blood Alcohol Content?
            </h3>
            <div class="blog-post" style="word-wrap: break-word; word-break: normal;">
                <p>
                    There are several factors that can influence your blood alcohol level:
                </p>
                <p style="font-weight:bold;">1. Size</p>
                <p>Generally, the smaller you are, the less alcohol you can consume to stay in compliance.</p>
                <p style="font-weight:bold;">2. Empty stomach</p>
                <p>
                    Drinking occurs more quickly to someone who hasn't eaten recently rather than
                    someone who just ate. In the absence of food, alcohol can be absorbed more rapidly
                    into the body. However, eating won't prevent a person from getting drunk.
                </p>
                <p style="font-weight:bold;">3. Body fat</p>
                <p>
                    People who have more body fat will get drunk quicker.
                </p>
                <p style="font-weight:bold;">4. Gender</p>
                <p>
                    The body of a woman absorbs alcohol more rapidly than that of a man, as women
                    generally have a lower ratio of fat to lean tissue. As a result, a woman who drinks the
                    same amount of alcohol as a man will have a higher blood alcohol level faster than the
                    man.
                </p>
                <p style="font-weight:bold;">5. Inexperience</p>
                <p>
                    Inexperienced drinkers usually have a lower tolerance to alcohol, which means that
                    their BAC rises faster than that of experienced drinkers.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    <h3 class="h3">To calculate the Alcohol Content in Blood</h3>
    <a class="btn btn-primary btn-lg" href="@Url.Action("Index", "BAC")" style="font-weight:700;">Blood Alcohol Concentration Calculator</a>

</div>

